            <fr:title text="Atomic vs compound sentences">Atomic vs compound sentences</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>            We already know about atomic sentences.
            A compound sentence is just any sentence that isn't atomic:
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2026</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>29</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/000U/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>000U</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/lectures/000U/</fr:route><fr:title text="Compound sentence">Compound sentence</fr:title><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>A <html:strong>compound sentence</html:strong> is any sentence that is not atomic.</html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
            So sentences like <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \land  q]]></fr:tex>, or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg  r]]></fr:tex>, or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex> are all compound sentences.
            Another way to think of it is: a compound sentence is any sentence that contains a connective.
</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
